# Tracking rules

Forge tracks two separate changelogs. Writing to the wrong one is the most common
tracking mistake — read this carefully.

## Two changelogs, two scopes

**`~/.forge/memory/forge-changelog.md` — global, Forge's own evolution**
Write here when Forge itself changes:
- A skill is ADDED, MODIFIED, or RETIRED
- A role or rule file is changed
- forge-start pulls an update from GitHub
- A Skill Smith HEALTH-CHECK runs

**`memory/forge-changelog.md` (in the current project) — per-project activity**
Write here for everything that happens inside a project:
- A skill is USED on a task
- A DECISION is made about the project
- forge-setup runs (SETUP)
- Reusable code is PROMOTED to @nathanokh/codebase

## Entry format (both files)
```
### YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM
- TYPE: [ADDED|MODIFIED|RETIRED|HEALTH-CHECK] (global only)
  OR
- TYPE: [USED|DECISION|SETUP|PROMOTED] (per-project only)
  target: [skill, role, or decision subject]
  by: [role name]
  project: [project name or "forge-itself"]
  reason: [one phrase]
```

## When to update forge-graph.md
The Skill Smith updates `~/.forge/memory/map/forge-graph.md` whenever a skill
is added, modified, or retired. This is the global Forge map — not per-project.

## When to update app-graph.md
Architect creates `memory/map/app-graph.md` in the current project.
Builder and Code Reviewer update node status. This is per-project only.

## API usage tracking

**Every time you call brave-search**, you MUST:
1. Read `memory/usage/usage.json` (path relative to this project, or `~/.forge/memory/usage/usage.json` if not present locally).
2. Increment `brave_search.calls_this_month` by 1.
3. Append an entry to `brave_search.daily_log`: `{"date": "YYYY-MM-DD", "calls": N, "project": "name"}`.
4. Update `brave_search.last_updated` to the current ISO timestamp.
5. Write the file back.
6. Calculate `pct = (calls_this_month / monthly_limit) * 100` and emit the appropriate warning below.

**Every time you call github MCP** tools (create_issue, push, PR, etc.):
- Increment `github.calls_this_month` by the number of API calls made.

**Every session start**, log estimated token usage to `tokens.sessions`:
`{"date": "YYYY-MM-DD", "project": "name", "estimated_tokens": N, "note": "brief task description"}`
Estimate: count your context window size in tokens if possible; otherwise use 5,000 as a baseline per session.

### Brave Search threshold warnings

After updating `usage.json`, emit the matching line in chat before proceeding:

| Threshold | Message to emit |
|-----------|----------------|
| >= 70% (700+ calls) | `[USAGE] Brave Search: 70% of monthly limit used (N/1000). Approaching limit.` |
| >= 80% (800+ calls) | `[USAGE WARNING] Brave Search: 80% used (N/1000). Consider batching queries.` |
| >= 90% (900+ calls) | `[USAGE ALERT] Brave Search: 90% used (N/1000). Use sparingly — 100 calls left.` |
| >= 95% (950+ calls) | `[USAGE CRITICAL] Brave Search: 95% used (N/1000). Pause and check with Approver before continuing.` |
| >= 99% (990+ calls) | `[USAGE LIMIT] Brave Search: 99% used (N/1000). STOP — do not call brave-search again this month without explicit Approver approval.` |

At 95%+, you MUST ask the Approver whether to continue before making another Brave call.

### Legacy: mcp-map.md
Also note major usage milestones in `memory/map/mcp-map.md` at the end of a task — but `usage.json` is the live source of truth.
